Most of all may this be true of their village life and land system. The possession of lands by village communities in some form is far too widespread and manifold to be a characteristic ol any people ⁴, and often seems to adapt itself to some preexistent institutions, or to survive in some ways or reassert itself where it has been more or less departed from, or otherwise to take different forms. Itis at least clear in Germany that we have the village as a subdivision ol the ‘pagus’ and that it regulated in some way the occupation ol the land comprised in it ⁶. The chiel description that we have might in most points approach to a description ol a free village under the ‘Mark' system ⁰. Yet it would be hold to say thatv permanent individual possession of land finds no place in the statement ⁷, or that there might not have been cases in which the whole village was a cluster of dependente ona common lord ⁸, or that other intermediate forms of tenure may not have been in existence. Great movements, such as those which launched the Teutonic tribes against the decaying · Roman empire, would lead naturally to great changes in ‘these · matters ⁹, and itis more remarkable that so much of the account given in this treatise should be recognizable than that so >much should have passed away.
